ment gaps versus D\u2019s temperament and leadership deficits (and B\u2019s numeric\u2011memory and teamwork issues, A\u2019s organizational and openness problems). The communication difficulty of C, while serious, appears more manageable than the hot\u2011tempered, know\u2011it\u2011all behavior of D, which could directly impair calmness and crew interaction on long\u2011haul flights.\n**Remaining uncertainty:** How frequently C\u2019s communication difficulties affect real\u2011time cockpit coordination and whether they can be mitigated through training or crew procedures.\n**What would change my vote:** Concrete evidence that D\u2019s temperament does not impact crew performance, or that another candidate possesses additional, unmentioned strengths that outweigh their listed weaknesses (e.g., strong teamwork evidence for A or B), or that C\u2019s communication issues have led to safety\u2011relevant operational problems.\nMETADATA_JSON:\n{\"agent\": \"agent_3\", \"vote\": \"Candidate C\"}", "thoughts": "We need to produce public message and metadata as agent_3. We have to consider the discussion so far. Agent 3 previously voted Candidate C. Now after seeing others' positions (Agent 2 now also C, Agent 1 C), we need to update position if needed. We must consider all candidates, weigh strengths/weaknesses, and possibly ask for missing info. The instruction says we can ask other agents using tools if we lack info about strengths. Do we have any missing positive attributes for A, B, D? We have all listed attributes. But maybe we lack any positive attributes for D beyond those listed. Agent 1 already said none. Agent 2 also hasn't provided any extra. So we might ask Agent 2 about any positive attributes for D? But we already have all. The instruction: \"If you cannot yet choose a candidate based on the available evidence, vote Undecided.\" But we have enough to choose. All agents now favor C. We need to produce public message summarizing our current preferred candidate (likely C), evidence, evidence from others, alternatives, tradeoff, uncertainty, what would change vote. Provide confidence.\n\nWe must not invent mitigation strategies. Just state evidence. Provide confidence maybe 70-80%.\n\nThus produce final answer."}
